"{\"uid\": \"inews.co.uk-news-france-train-network-arson-olympics-opening-ceremony-3190722\", \"text\": \"IMPARTIAL NEWS + INTELLIGENT DEBATE  Celine Dion has wowed crowds during a surprise performance at theParis Olympicsclosing ceremony.  The superstar singer made her first public performance since revealing she is living with stiff person syndrome after torchbearers France's judoka Teddy Riner and sprinter Marie-Jo Perec light the Olympic cauldron.  Organisers hung the France flag upside in an embarrassing blunder at the ceremony, which followed a day of chaos in France following arson attacks on the French railway network.  France national railway company SNCF said it will ensure transport for all Olympic delegations and has stepped up ground and air surveillance, including using 50 drones to monitor the country's rail network.  Among the athletes sailing down the Seine by boat included Team GB's Olympic hopefuls, include diver Tom Daley and Wimbledon champion Sir Andy Murray, who will be competing in his last games.  Follow theiliveblog for the latest updates.  Thanks for following along with us during this historic Olympics opening ceremony.  We will be leaving this blog here, but be sure to come back tomorrow for more live coverage as the first main day ofOlympicaction gets underway.  For now, here's some of the key events from today:  Celine Dion, halfway up the Eiffel Tower tonight, performed for the first time since revealing her diagnosis withstiff-person syndrome (SPS)in 2022.  The 56-year-old was forced\\u00a0tocancel tour dates and a Las Vegas residencyfollowing her diagnosis, and recently releaseda new documentarythat delves into her battle with the rare neurological condition.  Tonight, she delivered a performance typical of one of the world's most successful musicians.  It was just one song - a rendition ofHymne A L'Amour, a French classic \\u00c9dith Piaf - but the final act of the Paris 2024 opening ceremony felt both fitting, and encouraging to see Dion deliver so powerfully despite her autoimmune disease.  \\ud83e\\udd29@celinedionis spectacular and Paris sparkles with the Olympic spirit! \\u2728Paris 2024 is here!!! \\ud83c\\udf89#Paris2024#OpeningCeremonypic.twitter.com/es3KmnGD2k  American sprinter Michael Johnson and British swimmer Rebecca Adlington, two Olympic sporting greats of days gone by, are in theBBC studiowith Clare Balding, breaking down what we have just seen over the last few hours.  But they do not sound terribly taken by it all, with Adlington admitting she prefers opening ceremonies being held in stadiums as they usually are and adding that she felt this year's showing felt \\\"disjointed\\\".  Yours truly thought it was quite the show, even if it did feel like it dragged on a little by the end.  At least one X user agrees seems to agree with me on that:  That's my new favorite#OpeningCeremonyin#OlympicGameshistory. Yes even Beijing 08@celinedionGave a performance of a lifetime. That was as a historic performances that will be remembered forever. Got me emotional wow!Only flaw was it was an hour too longhttps://t.co/BrNwlpwY3z  PARIS- Celine sings us out, to the relief no doubt of soaked celebrities, who nonetheless whoop and cheer as the balloon drifts across the Paris skyline.  Tears on the set as overwhelmed television presenters succumb to the absolute Frenchness of it all.  The ever-spectacularCeline Dion, performing a rendition ofHymne A L'Amouron a stage halfway up the Eiffel Tower.  Quite the final act!  PARIS- The flame is lit, burning brightly in a balloon ascending above the Seine in tribute perhaps to French poet and novelist Jules Verne.  Let us hope it does not disappear around the world for 80 days.  That group of athletes has stopped running laps of the Louvre now but has grown to more than a dozen, including Charles Coste, France's oldest living Olympic champion, who is 100 years old!  He hands off to the final two, French judoka Teddy Riner and three-time Olympic gold medallist sprinter Marie-Jos\\u00e9 P\\u00e9rec,  who now stride up to the Olympic cauldron and light the flame, erupting a ring of fire seven metres wide that has given lift to an enormous hot air balloon.  And now Celine Dion is singing!  PARIS- The torch has spent 12 days in the French capital and appears no nearer lighting a flame.  Amelie Mauresmo presently out and about on the streets of Paris, high-fiving her way to the Louvre. Mauresmo now one of six athletes doing laps of the Louvre.  When will it end?  The Olympic flag appears to have been hoisted and flown upside down at the opening ceremony.  No comment on that yet from the relevant authorities, but you can see it below.  It's also unclear if it has been fixed yet.  NEW VIDEO: Olympic Flag hung upside down at Paris 2024 Opening Ceremony.pic.twitter.com/JylIpoSC6V  PARIS- Hard to imagine what Rafa Nadal andNadia Comanecihave to talk about but they are chatting away on the boat.  Comaneci being the retired Romanian gymnast who won five Olympic golds and was the first person to be awarded a perfect score of 10 in Olympic gymnastics.  PARIS- ZiZou back on the runway, hands the torch to that celebrated French hero, Rafa Nadal of Spain.  Sacre bleu!  The Olympic rings shine out from the Eiffel Tower. The rain is evaporating in the heat of anticipation.  Rafa now on a boat on the Seine channeling David Beckham before he hands the torch to Serena Williams and on to Carl Lewis.  They must have run out of French folk.  From one tennis all-time great to another, Nadal has now passed the Olympic torch to Serena Williams, sat alongside him on the boat.  And it's now in the hands of the other American on board, the track and field icon Carl Lewis. The three are sharing custody at the moment, it seems.  The rain is also back again in full force in Paris.  That's a headline I never thought I'd write.  We thought it was going to be Zinedine Zidane who carried the Olympic torch to light the flame - but maybe it'll be Rafa Nadal making the final leg of the journey?  The French football icon received the Olympic torch from our masked horserider, but has just handed it off to theSpanish tennis legendwho is now on board a boat flying down the Seine.  PARIS- As the Olympic oath is sworn, the top of the Eiffel Tower is barely visible through the cloud.  As the ceremony ticks well into its fourth hour, we have never needed the Olympic flame more - and fortunately Zinedine Zidane has just turned up.  The IOC president has handed over to French president Emmanuel Macron to officially open the2024 Paris Olympic Games.  And he has just done exactly that.  All that remains now is for the Olympic flame to be lit, after French flagbearers Florent Manaudou and M\\u00e9lina Robert-Michon finishing reading out the Olympic oath.  But who will take the torch and light the flame? Who else\\u2026 but Zizou!  PARIS- It's quite a sad scene inside the Trocadero now. IOC president Thomas Bach addresses maybe 2,500 people: a few hardy athletes, some poor camera operators and a few hundred very damp journalists.  Fortunately, those who left early are not missing much from Bach, who makes sure to thank \\\"the generous support of all our partners\\\".  He has at least managed to find someone to hold an umbrella over his head. (Rishi Sunak's lesson is learned.)  It's the turn of International Olympic Committee president Thomas Bach now.  He said: \\\"Finally, the moment has arrived - welcome to the Olympic Games Paris 2024. My heartfelt thanks go to our gracious French hosts. Thank you for welcoming us in such a spectacular way. The Olympic flame will make Paris and all of France shine even brighter.  \\\"We are deeply grateful to all our French friends. First and foremost, to the President of the French Republic. All our gratitude also goes to the public authorities at all levels as well as the Paris 2024 Organising Committee, under the excellent leadership of my fellow Olympian, Tony Estanguet.  \\\"You are bringing our Olympic Agenda reforms to life by making these Games wide open. All of us will experience Olympic Games that are more inclusive, more urban, younger and more sustainable - the first Olympic Games with full gender parity on the field of play.  \\\"A special thanks goes to the thousands of volunteers. Thank you for your commitment. Your smiles make us fall in love even more with Paris and France. Our thanks also go to whole team of the Organising Committee, of the public services and to everyone who is contributing to make these Olympic Games an unforgettable experience.  \\\"What better place than Paris, to share this magic of the Olympic Games with the whole world.\\\"  Paris 2024 president Tony Estanguet, a three-time Olympic gold medallist in canoe slalom, is speaking now.  \\\"France is often said to be the country of love,\\\" he said. \\\"One thing I know is that here, when we love, we truly love. And between France and the Games, there has been a big love story\\\".  Mr Estanguet said carrying on the legacy \\\"born nearly 130 years ago\\\" was \\\"a huge responsibility, so we have put our whole hearts into it. To love the Games is to court the Games for 100 years, for the chance to bring them back to Paris.  \\\"When you are madly in love with the Games, you feel like you can do anything. We have been bold, doing things that have never been done before, like having this opening ceremony in the city for the first time in the history of the Olympic Games.  \\\"Like every host country our ambition has been to help the Games grow stronger.\\\"  Addressing the thousands of athletes in attendance, he said: \\\"What a sight it is to see you all parading together. What a rare and precious moment you have given us. And even though the Games cannot solve every problem, even though discrimination and conflicts are not about to disappear, tonight you have reminded us how beautiful humanity is when we come together.  \\\"And when you return to the Olympic Village, you will be sending a message of hope to the whole world, that there is a place where people of every nationality, every culture and every religion can live together. You will be reminding us of what's possible.  \\\"For the next 16 days, you will be the best version of humanity. You will remind us that the emotions of sport form a universal language that we all share. Until the 11th of August, we will be by your side.  \\\"Your defeats will be our defeats. Your victories will be our victories. Your emotions will be our emotions.\\\"  The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, Filippo Grandi, has been given the Olympic Laurel.  Introduced in 2016, the Olympic Laurel is awarded by the Interational Olympic Committee (IOC) to honour \\\"significant achievements in education, culture, development and peace through sport\\\".  Said mechanical horse has been swapped for a real horse now, a white one which our still-masked individual is riding - more slowly now - in front of the Eiffel Tower and a parade of the participating countries' flags.  Quite the sight.  And would you believe it, the rain has stopped!  They have dismounted and are carrying the Olympic flag, folded in their arms towards the waiting dignitaries.  The flag has been delivered, and will be raised again as the Olympic anthem begins to play.  Getting word from Kevin Garside, our chief sports correspondent who's out in Paris, that our horseback rider was Floriane Issert, a warrant officer in the Gendarmerie.  Impartial news + intelligent debate  All rights reserved. \\u00a9 2025 Associated Newspapers Limited.\"}"